lements**\n\nI'm now revising the design for the primary UI buttons. I'm focusing on \"Provision Identity\", a much better CTA. I'm imagining a high-tech visual. I am also adjusting the look and feel, and am now focusing on refining the overall flow. I'm exploring an aesthetically balanced split-screen layout.\n\n\n**Designing Phase 4 Banner**\n\nI'm now implementing the Phase 4 emulation banner. I'm focusing on its design and how it should look. It is designed to be a high-tech notice, as per the mockup. The plan is to clearly signal the local emulation and a simulated cryptographic RBAC sandbox.\n\n\n**Simulating OAuth2 Endpoints**\n\nI'm working on simulating OAuth2 endpoints and building the \"Verify Vanguard OIDC Handshake\" button. I'll need to make sure the button triggers an emulation of a zero-knowledge mock handshake. The goal is to simulate access with secure and realistic OAuth2 protocols. I'm focusing on providing users with a button for a seamless, secure, and accurate simulation.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Handshake Logging**\n\nI'm now detailing the modal that will display the simulated OAuth2 handshake logs. I'm focusing on making the logs visually appealing. The styling will include an amber terminal icon, uppercase text, and a dark background. The logs will dynamically appear within the modal.\n\n\n**Visualizing Terminal Logs**\n\nI'm now focusing on the aesthetic details of the OAuth2 handshake log modal. I'm adding styling to make the modal's internal logs clear and easy to read. I'm leveraging distinct text colors, formatting, and a dark background for the log messages. The design will use an amber terminal icon.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Terminal Simulation**\n\nI'm now putting the finishing touches on the simulated OAuth2 handshake terminal output. I've included the key cryptographic details. I'm making sure it matches the desired look and feel perfectly, and matches the Phase 5 Readiness. The terminal will clearly indicate the successful handshake.\n\n